WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.760
There we see a wreck, and there we see something in there.

00:02.760 --> 00:07.000
And then this thing popping up on the screen.

00:08.940 --> 00:12.300
My next guest is a world-famous treasure hunter.

00:12.460 --> 00:13.400
You heard that right.

00:15.100 --> 00:17.520
His name is Dennis Asperg.

00:17.600 --> 00:20.580
And this Swedish sensation is a real-life superhero

00:20.580 --> 00:22.040
out of a different era.

00:22.300 --> 00:23.440
I'm a curious guy.

00:23.620 --> 00:25.940
I've always been interested in finding things

00:25.940 --> 00:27.160
that nobody else has found.

00:27.160 --> 00:30.780
But on June 19th, 2011,

00:31.100 --> 00:33.360
his life's mission would change forever.

00:33.620 --> 00:35.440
From unearthing human treasure

00:35.440 --> 00:38.480
to unraveling the nature of reality itself.

00:38.960 --> 00:42.840
That's when he came upon what you might call an underwater UFO,

00:43.280 --> 00:45.800
or what's now known as a USO,

00:46.120 --> 00:50.860
an unidentified submersible object in the very remote Baltic Sea.

00:51.360 --> 00:55.880
It's something that makes our instrument go wild sometimes.

00:57.160 --> 01:00.500
It's on the ocean floor right now.

01:00.780 --> 01:03.720
So me, my crew, and Ammar Kandil from Yes Theory

01:03.720 --> 01:05.000
went to go see it.

01:05.620 --> 01:07.960
Sitting 90 meters below the surface,

01:08.400 --> 01:09.680
60 meters wide,

01:09.920 --> 01:11.780
this is one of the weirdest objects

01:11.780 --> 01:14.240
ever detected by humans in the ocean.

01:14.580 --> 01:14.860
Period.

01:14.860 --> 01:16.460
Yeah, it's round,

01:16.580 --> 01:18.200
and then we have these corridors.

01:18.440 --> 01:20.620
You have angles, 90 degrees angles.

01:20.820 --> 01:22.420
When you say corridors, like...

01:22.420 --> 01:23.500
Yeah, you have a corridor,

01:23.740 --> 01:25.380
and you have walls, flat walls.

01:25.560 --> 01:26.000
Wow.

01:27.520 --> 01:28.900
Dennis has now confirmed

01:28.900 --> 01:31.980
that it is not attached to the seabed floor,

01:32.100 --> 01:34.500
so it's not a natural geological formation.

01:34.860 --> 01:37.440
I have never seen anything like that before,

01:37.560 --> 01:39.340
not have my colleagues either.

01:39.340 --> 01:44.040
Electromagnetic anomalies are rampant around it.

01:44.300 --> 01:47.680
It breaks down GPS, subsea rovers, drones.

01:47.680 --> 01:49.920
And then when we have used the Aero-V,

01:50.320 --> 01:51.740
the Aero-V stops working.

01:52.180 --> 01:52.500
Really?

01:52.680 --> 01:52.880
Yep.

01:53.120 --> 01:53.960
You lost GPS?

01:54.340 --> 01:55.680
You were close to the...

01:55.680 --> 01:56.460
To the object?

01:56.580 --> 01:56.780
Yeah.

01:57.680 --> 01:58.660
Oh, my God.

01:59.120 --> 02:00.740
We have video of smoke

02:00.740 --> 02:03.500
coming out of the water above the object,

02:03.620 --> 02:05.920
as if it's fuming or emitting gas.

02:05.920 --> 02:08.920
And then you see, like, it's from this hole,

02:09.640 --> 02:11.260
this milk is going...

02:11.260 --> 02:11.580
Uh-huh.

02:11.660 --> 02:11.980
...and on.

02:12.280 --> 02:12.760
Like it was...

02:12.760 --> 02:13.700
Something is moving.

02:13.860 --> 02:14.540
Yes, breathing.

02:14.540 --> 02:14.940
Breathing.

02:15.020 --> 02:15.200
Yeah.

02:16.100 --> 02:18.920
Almost like a biological organism or something.

02:19.920 --> 02:21.600
But it doesn't stop there.

02:21.800 --> 02:24.000
It was literally struck by lightning,

02:24.580 --> 02:27.040
an occurrence often considered a high watermark

02:27.040 --> 02:28.300
for its unlikeliness.

02:28.660 --> 02:30.980
We also have video of NATO ships

02:30.980 --> 02:32.480
encircling this object

02:32.480 --> 02:34.980
and tracking Dennis' Ocean X crew

02:34.980 --> 02:36.660
in the middle of the Baltic Sea.

02:36.780 --> 02:39.360
We had a meeting at the headquarter in Stockholm.

02:39.700 --> 02:41.880
I said to one of the people there,

02:41.980 --> 02:42.820
have you been there?

02:42.880 --> 02:43.860
Have you dive on it?

02:44.440 --> 02:45.740
And he just looked at me,

02:45.900 --> 02:46.660
no, no, no, no.

02:47.100 --> 02:48.280
We have not been there.

02:48.740 --> 02:50.020
But I'm filming you.

02:50.140 --> 02:50.960
I have filmed you.

02:51.100 --> 02:52.340
So I know you have been there.

02:53.180 --> 02:53.520
Nothing.

02:53.700 --> 02:54.460
He don't say anything.

02:54.580 --> 02:54.940
Whoa.

02:56.860 --> 02:58.640
You'll get to see the full extent

02:58.640 --> 03:01.120
of what we found at the end of this video.

03:01.120 --> 03:04.000
Whether this is an ancient sacred temple,

03:04.440 --> 03:06.700
a crashed unidentified flying object,

03:06.900 --> 03:09.620
or an unidentified submersible object,

03:09.980 --> 03:11.800
whatever this thing is,

03:11.960 --> 03:13.520
it's definitively weird.

03:14.000 --> 03:17.020
And like the object under the mesa at Skinwalker Ranch,

03:17.260 --> 03:19.620
it seems to have a life of its own.

03:20.000 --> 03:21.240
So without further ado,

03:21.500 --> 03:22.800
sit back, relax,

03:22.920 --> 03:25.620
and prepare to take a deep dive into the abyss

03:25.620 --> 03:28.920
with this week's amazing Swedish alchemist,

03:29.240 --> 03:30.460
Dennis Asperg.

03:44.460 --> 03:47.660
So we're 60 kilometers out at sea,

03:47.840 --> 03:50.920
kind of the epicenter between Finland and Sweden.

03:55.620 --> 03:56.800
We're right above the spot,

03:56.960 --> 03:58.840
right above the Baltic Sea anomaly.

04:00.040 --> 04:02.120
And it just feels like we're in the middle of the ocean,

04:02.220 --> 04:02.740
to be honest.

04:02.820 --> 04:06.480
It doesn't feel any different than anywhere else.

04:09.420 --> 04:11.180
One of our videographers, Phillip,

04:12.020 --> 04:13.640
unfortunately threw up.

04:16.900 --> 04:18.300
I think I'm the only person

04:18.300 --> 04:21.060
who hasn't taken the seasickness medication,

04:21.300 --> 04:23.260
which is probably pretty stupid.

04:25.620 --> 04:33.380
Now we're sending the ROV down,

04:34.040 --> 04:36.340
the remote-operated vehicle,

04:37.300 --> 04:39.220
and we can see what it sees,

04:39.300 --> 04:40.720
although visibility will be low,

04:40.840 --> 04:43.060
so you can only see maybe max,

04:43.220 --> 04:44.420
maybe a foot in front of it.

04:44.740 --> 04:47.080
And then we're also going to be doing some sonar scanning

04:47.080 --> 04:49.720
and try to get a better understanding

04:49.720 --> 04:51.440
of the 3D structure

04:51.440 --> 04:54.220
that we're looking at with the Baltic Sea anomalies.

04:54.220 --> 04:57.100
And how deep is the object?

04:57.400 --> 04:58.220
90 meters.

04:58.520 --> 04:59.140
90 meters.

04:59.220 --> 04:59.380
Yeah.

05:02.260 --> 05:04.940
It's a very unconventional career that you have.

05:05.280 --> 05:08.480
When did you start to get into treasure hunting

05:08.480 --> 05:11.740
and exploring all of these unknown things in the ocean?

05:13.640 --> 05:15.960
Exploring and have been interesting in history

05:15.960 --> 05:17.080
and all that thing,

05:17.160 --> 05:18.620
have been since I was a kid.

05:18.620 --> 05:21.880
Something I grew up with with my parents

05:21.880 --> 05:24.880
because they were also interesting in that area

05:24.880 --> 05:27.960
to find out things and search for things

05:27.960 --> 05:29.800
that nobody else have found.

05:30.000 --> 05:31.360
So it's a natural thing.

05:31.500 --> 05:33.760
I have, you know, grown up in a family

05:33.760 --> 05:35.680
that works, not works,

05:35.760 --> 05:37.300
but have an interest in that field.

05:37.640 --> 05:38.560
So...

05:38.560 --> 05:39.940
Was your father an explorer?

05:40.260 --> 05:41.740
No, he was a diver,

05:41.740 --> 05:43.780
but he had an other job also,

05:43.900 --> 05:45.160
but he was a diver also.

05:45.200 --> 05:45.300
Okay.

05:45.520 --> 05:45.720
Yeah.

05:46.080 --> 05:47.780
And did you grow up, you know,

05:47.860 --> 05:49.400
reading about explorers?

05:49.400 --> 05:50.620
Yeah, that was the...

05:50.620 --> 05:51.460
Yeah, yeah, of course.

05:51.660 --> 05:54.260
Reading history books, of course,

05:54.460 --> 05:57.680
and fictions also,

05:57.800 --> 06:00.460
and going into these things

06:00.460 --> 06:02.780
with the treasures and shipwrecks

06:02.780 --> 06:05.600
that have disappeared with interesting cargo.

06:05.960 --> 06:07.940
So that has been interesting for me

06:07.940 --> 06:08.720
and, you know,

06:08.900 --> 06:10.780
that has always been the interest for me.

06:10.780 --> 06:12.260
What was the first shipwreck

06:12.260 --> 06:13.140
you went looking for?

06:13.420 --> 06:15.900
When I really go into commercial diving

06:15.900 --> 06:18.660
and in that area was for...

06:18.660 --> 06:22.260
I mean, it must be 15, 20, 20 years ago.

06:23.100 --> 06:26.100
And it was together with Peter Lindberg,

06:26.220 --> 06:26.960
my friend,

06:27.180 --> 06:30.740
and we did exploration in the Baltic Sea

06:30.740 --> 06:33.600
and we found wrecks with liquor,

06:34.320 --> 06:35.600
cognac and wine

06:35.600 --> 06:37.100
and different type of things.

06:37.280 --> 06:37.960
Booth ships.

06:38.860 --> 06:39.800
That's the money.

06:39.800 --> 06:40.640
That's...

06:40.640 --> 06:42.100
The booze are still valuable.

06:42.300 --> 06:42.940
Yeah, of course.

06:43.140 --> 06:43.400
Of course.

06:43.520 --> 06:45.520
And it's still drinkable and...

06:45.520 --> 06:48.280
Yeah, some bottles are still drinkable.

06:48.460 --> 06:52.520
We found also one of the oldest wine in the world

06:52.520 --> 06:53.280
from 1600.

06:53.820 --> 06:54.060
Wow.

06:54.160 --> 06:54.660
Drinkable.

06:54.920 --> 06:55.500
Oh my God.

06:55.540 --> 06:58.940
And cognac on its way to this Russian Tsar.

07:00.160 --> 07:00.640
Drinkable.

07:00.800 --> 07:02.820
And we have tried it also, Peter and I,

07:02.880 --> 07:04.480
and it was very strong.

07:04.480 --> 07:05.320
Unbelievable.

07:05.440 --> 07:05.700
Yeah.

07:05.940 --> 07:09.480
What's some of the more interesting shipwrecks

07:09.480 --> 07:10.160
that you found,

07:10.240 --> 07:11.520
or maybe one in particular

07:11.520 --> 07:14.140
that you remember that has a story attached to it?

07:14.140 --> 07:15.080
Except the Baltic Sea anomaly.

07:15.080 --> 07:16.360
Except the Baltic Sea anomaly.

07:16.360 --> 07:17.580
We're building up to that.

07:17.820 --> 07:17.860
Wow.

07:18.040 --> 07:20.300
It's many, I must say.

07:20.420 --> 07:24.580
But one very interesting wreck we found

07:24.580 --> 07:26.260
was 2015.

07:26.480 --> 07:29.300
We found the Russian Tsar's submarine, SOM.

07:29.740 --> 07:30.120
Wow.

07:30.280 --> 07:32.720
Yeah, built in US, 1904.

07:33.100 --> 07:33.740
Oh my God.

07:33.820 --> 07:35.720
And the Russian Tsar bought it

07:35.720 --> 07:38.100
and used it in the war against Japan.

07:38.580 --> 07:38.900
Uh-huh.

07:39.020 --> 07:42.440
And it was out on a mission

07:42.440 --> 07:44.220
in the Swedish water.

07:44.680 --> 07:46.020
Should not be in the Swedish water.

07:46.180 --> 07:46.440
Uh-huh.

07:46.480 --> 07:46.900
It was.

07:47.080 --> 07:47.340
Uh-huh.

07:47.800 --> 07:49.380
And it was a collision

07:49.380 --> 07:51.460
between a Swedish cargo ship

07:51.460 --> 07:52.440
and this submarine.

07:52.780 --> 07:54.820
So the periscope went off

07:54.820 --> 07:58.500
and 18-man down to the bottom.

07:58.500 --> 07:59.160
How do you,

07:59.260 --> 08:00.960
what sensors do you use

08:00.960 --> 08:02.460
to locate an object?

08:03.060 --> 08:04.460
Uh, it's very easy.

08:04.580 --> 08:05.820
It's a side-scan sonar.

08:06.060 --> 08:08.380
It's a sonar that looks down

08:08.380 --> 08:10.760
to the image you get.

08:10.960 --> 08:11.220
Okay.

08:11.380 --> 08:11.780
Of it.

08:12.020 --> 08:13.120
Uh, so,

08:13.240 --> 08:14.500
and then we use ROV

08:14.500 --> 08:16.660
and of course we have dive on it also.

08:16.860 --> 08:17.520
What's ROV?

08:17.860 --> 08:19.860
A remote operating robot,

08:20.000 --> 08:21.020
you know, underwater.

08:21.380 --> 08:22.320
A little sub-seedule.

08:22.320 --> 08:22.960
Yeah, exactly.

08:23.140 --> 08:23.420
Okay.

08:23.720 --> 08:24.980
So that we have used

08:24.980 --> 08:27.080
and after that,

08:27.160 --> 08:28.520
we did dives on it also

08:28.520 --> 08:31.020
to really identify it

08:31.020 --> 08:32.840
and see if it was that submarine

08:32.840 --> 08:33.300
we have,

08:33.680 --> 08:34.500
we thought it was.

08:34.620 --> 08:35.300
So interesting.

08:35.400 --> 08:36.340
And so when you find

08:36.340 --> 08:37.600
these shipwrecks,

08:37.740 --> 08:38.200
you know,

08:38.340 --> 08:38.980
uh,

08:39.360 --> 08:40.840
with cognac and wine

08:40.840 --> 08:41.520
and that sort of thing,

08:41.560 --> 08:42.260
is this your business?

08:42.520 --> 08:43.520
Do you then go out

08:43.520 --> 08:44.980
and sell that on the open market?

08:44.980 --> 08:45.500
Oh, I wish.

08:45.620 --> 08:45.940
I wish.

08:46.140 --> 08:46.460
I wish.

08:46.900 --> 08:47.640
Do you know?

08:47.800 --> 08:48.760
Or do you have financiers?

08:48.760 --> 08:49.080
No, we have,

08:49.260 --> 08:49.980
as you know,

08:50.040 --> 08:51.240
we have the situation here

08:51.240 --> 08:53.200
as we have in other countries

08:53.200 --> 08:54.580
in the whole world

08:54.580 --> 08:55.680
with the pandemic

08:55.680 --> 08:56.820
and the virus

08:56.820 --> 08:58.040
and also the,

08:58.040 --> 08:59.700
the war

08:59.700 --> 09:00.680
and lots of things

09:00.680 --> 09:01.360
are going on.

09:01.400 --> 09:02.420
So it has not been easy.

09:03.020 --> 09:03.420
Uh,

09:03.420 --> 09:05.120
so we tried to sell this,

09:05.500 --> 09:05.820
uh,

09:05.820 --> 09:06.920
wine and cognac

09:06.920 --> 09:08.080
and things on the market

09:08.080 --> 09:10.080
and the interest was zero.

09:10.320 --> 09:10.520
Mm.

09:10.640 --> 09:10.940
Now,

09:11.180 --> 09:12.160
nobody was interested.

09:12.300 --> 09:12.900
No way.

09:13.020 --> 09:13.220
No.

09:13.440 --> 09:14.100
That's why you said

09:14.100 --> 09:14.720
you drank it.

09:14.940 --> 09:15.200
Yeah,

09:15.200 --> 09:16.360
I drank it myself.

09:16.360 --> 09:17.380
at home now

09:17.380 --> 09:17.860
instead.

09:18.500 --> 09:18.740
No,

09:18.900 --> 09:19.420
uh,

09:19.420 --> 09:19.660
no,

09:19.660 --> 09:19.840
no.

09:20.160 --> 09:21.360
So it has been very difficult

09:21.360 --> 09:22.660
because we have spent

09:22.660 --> 09:23.680
lots of time

09:23.680 --> 09:24.800
and money on this project

09:24.800 --> 09:25.820
because we believe

09:25.820 --> 09:26.440
this can,

09:26.440 --> 09:27.720
this can finance

09:27.720 --> 09:28.820
our other projects.

09:28.900 --> 09:29.100
Yeah.

09:29.460 --> 09:30.140
But the interest

09:30.140 --> 09:31.160
has been weak,

09:31.440 --> 09:32.260
very weak

09:32.260 --> 09:33.240
when it's come to that.

09:33.480 --> 09:33.920
Interesting.

09:34.260 --> 09:34.440
Yeah.

09:34.820 --> 09:36.380
So do you ever,

09:36.460 --> 09:37.720
are you ever able to sell

09:37.720 --> 09:39.240
or make a business

09:39.240 --> 09:39.960
out of,

09:40.040 --> 09:40.280
you know,

09:40.320 --> 09:41.360
some of the stuff you find

09:41.360 --> 09:42.080
or is it mostly

09:42.080 --> 09:43.320
just for passion

09:43.320 --> 09:44.200
or for history?

09:44.200 --> 09:44.360
No, no.

09:44.360 --> 09:44.840
I mean,

09:44.880 --> 09:45.460
in that case,

09:45.460 --> 09:46.020
when it's talking

09:46.020 --> 09:47.440
about the bottles

09:47.440 --> 09:48.520
of champagne

09:48.520 --> 09:49.140
and cognac

09:49.140 --> 09:49.920
and wine

09:49.920 --> 09:50.760
and things like that,

09:51.600 --> 09:51.900
of course,

09:51.960 --> 09:52.500
we have it

09:52.500 --> 09:53.680
and hopefully

09:53.680 --> 09:54.440
we're going to sell it

09:54.440 --> 09:54.980
in the future.

09:55.200 --> 09:55.320
Yeah.

09:55.320 --> 09:56.140
But I don't,

09:56.260 --> 09:56.800
you know,

09:56.880 --> 09:57.400
I won't have

09:57.400 --> 09:58.520
lots of money for it.

09:58.560 --> 09:59.140
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

09:59.140 --> 10:01.640
So, but that is something

10:01.640 --> 10:03.060
I don't think about

10:03.060 --> 10:03.680
so much now.

10:03.880 --> 10:04.760
Should invite myself

10:04.760 --> 10:05.560
over for a drink.

10:05.640 --> 10:06.460
You can get the drink,

10:06.600 --> 10:06.860
of course.

10:08.120 --> 10:09.160
Tell us about

10:09.160 --> 10:10.520
the Baltic Sea anomaly.

10:10.520 --> 10:11.240
The Baltic Sea anomaly,

10:11.400 --> 10:11.520
yeah.

10:11.520 --> 10:12.240
What is it?

10:12.360 --> 10:13.560
Wow, good question.

10:13.900 --> 10:15.100
The Baltic Sea anomaly,

10:15.280 --> 10:15.500
okay,

10:15.600 --> 10:16.640
it begins like this.

10:16.900 --> 10:17.740
We were out

10:17.740 --> 10:18.360
on a mission,

10:19.180 --> 10:20.500
this time to find

10:20.500 --> 10:20.940
a wreck,

10:21.060 --> 10:21.700
special wreck

10:21.700 --> 10:22.800
with champagne on it.

10:22.800 --> 10:25.360
We were out

10:25.360 --> 10:27.360
for almost a week

10:27.360 --> 10:28.240
and then we have

10:28.240 --> 10:29.360
problems with the boat

10:29.360 --> 10:30.340
that began to leak

10:30.340 --> 10:31.440
and we almost sunk

10:31.440 --> 10:32.100
with the boat.

10:32.480 --> 10:34.300
So it was very scary

10:34.300 --> 10:35.860
but we managed

10:35.860 --> 10:36.920
to come to a harbor

10:36.920 --> 10:37.540
in Finland

10:37.540 --> 10:39.760
to repair the boat

10:39.760 --> 10:41.340
and we had been out

10:41.340 --> 10:42.300
for one week then.

10:43.080 --> 10:44.040
And then we decided

10:44.040 --> 10:44.580
to go out

10:44.580 --> 10:45.700
to a new area

10:45.700 --> 10:46.680
and search there

10:46.680 --> 10:48.020
with the Sidescan Zona

10:48.020 --> 10:48.920
to see if we find

10:48.920 --> 10:50.060
this special wreck.

10:52.800 --> 10:57.820
We were out

10:57.820 --> 10:59.020
and we searched

10:59.020 --> 11:00.080
in a new area.

11:01.120 --> 11:02.820
We were quite tired,

11:02.940 --> 11:03.380
I must say,

11:03.600 --> 11:04.420
after one week

11:04.420 --> 11:04.980
and then we had

11:04.980 --> 11:05.880
all the problems

11:05.880 --> 11:06.520
with the boat,

11:06.600 --> 11:07.560
the leaking and so on.

11:07.640 --> 11:08.880
So we were tired

11:08.880 --> 11:09.680
and disappointed.

11:09.880 --> 11:10.680
We have not found

11:10.680 --> 11:11.440
the wreck yet.

11:11.740 --> 11:12.540
But now we're going

11:12.540 --> 11:13.740
to search in a new area

11:13.740 --> 11:14.380
and hopefully

11:14.380 --> 11:15.340
we're going to find it.

11:16.780 --> 11:17.540
It was nighttime,

11:17.820 --> 11:19.040
